`Request` and `Response` are interfaces with same methods. We can introduce additional interfaces:
```
public interface Head {
    Iterable<String> head() throws IOException;
}

public interface Body {
    InputStream body() throws IOException;
}
```

With that we can rewrite `Request` and `Response` in this way:
```
public interface Request extends Head, Body {
}

public interface Response extends Head, Body {
}
```

This might be useful for example for `AbstractHmHeader` that could be rewritten as follows:
```
public final HmHeader<T extends Head> extends TypeSafeMatcher<T> {
    // relevant methods
}
```

The difference is that we don't need `HmRsHeader` and `HmRqHeader` classes anymore as we can use `head` method directly in `HmHeader`. Those classes are duplicates of each other and they just provide `head` method which can be used directly if we have those base classes. There also might be other use cases for that.

