A useful Fork would be a Fork chain, that routes to each Fork in order until one returns a result, or until none are left.

Here is a suggested implementation. Please add unit tests.

``` java
/**
 * A {@link Fork} chain. Routes to each {@link Fork} in order until one returns
 * a response or until none are left.
 * @author Felipe Pina (felipe.pina@protonmail.com)
 * @version $Id$
 * @since 0.32
 */
public final class FkChain implements Fork {

    /**
     * Forks.
     */
    private final transient Collection<Fork> forks;

    /**
     * Ctor.
     */
    public FkChain() {
        this(Collections.<Fork>emptyList());
    }

    /**
     * Ctor.
     * @param forks Forks
     */
    public FkChain(final Fork... forks) {
        this(Arrays.asList(forks));
    }

    /**
     * Ctor.
     * @param forks Forks
     */
    public FkChain(final Collection<Fork> forks) {
        this.forks = Collections.unmodifiableCollection(forks);
    }

    @Override
    public Opt<Response> route(final Request request) throws IOException {
        Opt<Response> response = new Opt.Empty<>();
        for (final Fork fork : this.forks) {
            final Opt<Response> current = fork.route(request);
            if (current.has()) {
                response = current;
                break;
            }
        }
        return response;
    }
```

Also, the implementation of `TkFork` can be simplified by the use of `FkChain`..

HTTP response header usually has content-type header value with definition of charset. This charset must be taken into account when characters of the body are converted to bytes using the body() method.
But most (if not all) implementations of this method uses default charset, not that defined in the header.
This can happen indirectly, like in constructor 

```
public  RsWithBody(final Response res, final CharSequence body) {
        this(res, body.toString().getBytes());
    }
```

Here getBytes() use default charset instead of the charset defined in the header.

As a result, client which receives byte stream cannot reconstruct the characters of the response body.

