Currently Href uses following code for extracting server+path from URL:

```
final URI link = URI.create(txt);
final String query = link.getQuery();
...
final String href = link.toString();
this.uri = URI.create(
    href.substring(0, href.length() - query.length() - 1)
);
```

(see https://github.com/yegor256/takes/blob/b536a61c7631d6d1b8bda6d1675eb6b823311528/src/main/java/org/takes/misc/Href.java#L73)

The above code works when query part has only standard not encoded elements, but when the URL is like: `http://localhost:8080/doc/read?file=%5B%5D%28%29.txt` it breaks because `query` contains already decoded data (in this case: `file=[]().txt`) but `href` has stil encoded data, so doing substring on it leads to `http://localhost:8080/doc/read?file=%5`, while it should be `http://localhost:8080/doc/read`.

This can be fixed if instead of `link.getQuery()` one will use `link.getRawQuery()`.

